The IBM Time Sharing System <b>TSS/360</b> was an early <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../958/30958.xml">
time-sharing</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../194/22194.xml">
operating system</link> which ran on a special model of the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../294/29294.xml">
System/360</link> line of mainframes, the <platform wordnetid="103961939" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<surface wordnetid="104362025" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<horizontal_surface wordnetid="103536348" confidence="0.8">
<device wordnetid="103183080" confidence="0.8">
<machine wordnetid="103699975" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../024/7522024.xml">
Model 67</link></machine>
</device>
</horizontal_surface>
</instrumentality>
</surface>
</artifact>
</platform>
. Introduced in 1967, it implemented a number of novel features which eventually saw daylight in more popular systems such as <O wordnetid="106832680" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../847/18847.xml">
Multics</link></O>
 and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../018/315018.xml">
VM/CMS</link>.
